data.content:
**Every synchronous call in your repository will throw at runtime in .NET 11.**

In EF Core 10, the Cosmos DB provider deprecated sync I/O but allowed a sync-over-async opt-in. **In EF Core 11, that opt-in is gone** — calling any sync API (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) **always throws**, with no workaround.

You must convert to async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:** `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`.

Note that this will ripple through your call chain — every caller must also become `async`/`await` up to the controller level (which ASP.NET Core already supports natively).
